ierarchies. In response to these changes, Indian Muslim artisans began publicly asserting the deep relation between their religion and their labor, using the increasingly accessible popular press to redefine Islamic traditions "from below." Centering the stories and experiences of metalsmiths, stonemasons, tailors, press workers, and carpenters, Pious Labor examines colonial-era social and technological changes through the perspectives of the workers themselves. As Amanda Lanzillo shows, the colonial marginalization of these artisans is intimately linked with the continued exclusion of laboring voices today. By drawing on previously unstudied Urdu-language technical manuals and community histories, Lanzillo highlights not only the materiality of artisanal production but also the cultural agency of artisanal producers, filling in a major gap in South Asian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamzIndia, Northy19th century. 0aIslamzIndia, Northy20th century. 0aMuslim artisanszIndia, Northy19th century. 0aMuslim artisanszIndia, Northy20th century. 0aTechnologyzIndia, Northy19th century. 0aTechnologyzIndia, Northy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Islamic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520398580zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520398580zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520398580/original  a978-3-11-079135-8 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA